{
  "texts": [
    "Firstly, measuring some important clinical variables (e.g., disease stage) relies heavily on the clinician's individual interpretation, which may introduce human bias, thereby reducing the accuracy and reliability of the prediction results 1.",
    "Interestingly, the study 5 showed that ML model can give more accurate predictions than the attending physicians in cancer survival analysis.",
    "Secondly, small sample size accompanied by high-dimensional input data (e.g., gene expression data, whole slide image, etc.)",
    "can result in overfitting 6 and hamper the generalizability of existing models.",
    "Thirdly, the relationship between predictors and survival outcome may be non-linear 7, and thus existing models that assume a linear relationship (e.g., Cox Proportional Hazards model 8) may produce inaccurate results."
  ]
}